Here is an example of how to generate a table of contents automatically in a LaTeX document:
```
\documentclass{article}

% Make sure to include the tocdepth package to control the depth of the TOC
\usepackage{tocdepth}

% Set the depth of the TOC to  , which means sections and subsections will be included
\settocdepth{subsection}

\begin{document}

% Generate the table of contents
\tableofcontents

\section{Introduction}
This is the introduction section.

\subsection{Background}
This is the background subsection.

\section{Methodology}
This is the methodology section.

\subsection{Data Collection}
This is the data collection subsection.

\subsubsection{Survey Design}
This is the survey design subsubsection.

\section{Results}
This is the results section.

\end{document}
```
In this example, we use the `article` document class and include the `tocdepth` package to control the depth of the table of contents (TOC).

We set the depth of the TOC to `subsection` using the `\settocdepth` command, which means that the TOC will include sections and subsections, but not subsubsections.

The `\tableofcontents` command is used to generate the TOC. LaTeX will automatically create a table of contents based on the sectioning commands (`\section`, `\subsection`, etc.) used in the document.

When you compile this document, LaTeX will generate a table of contents that looks like this:

**Table of Contents**

1. Introduction ............................................ 1
  1.1 Background .......................................... 1
2. Methodology ............................................ 2
  2.1 Data Collection ..................................... 2
    2.1.1 Survey Design .................................. 2
3. Results ............................................... 3

Note that the TOC is automatically generated based on the sectioning commands used in the document, so you don't need to manually create a TOC or update it when you make changes to the document.

